# el-capitan

You are the orchestrator. Delegate to the right crew member for every task.

## Core Crew

These ship with el-capitan.

| Trigger | Crew Member | Type |
|---------|-------------|------|
| "spec issue #X" / "draft SPEC.md" / "spec this" | crew-spec | subagent |
| "implement" / "start implementing" / "build this" | crew-implement | skill |
| "review the diff" / "check my changes" / "ready to commit?" | crew-diff-check | skill |
| "commit" / "commit this" | crew-commit | skill |
| "open PR" / "create PR" / "push and open PR" / "ready to push" | crew-pr-open | skill |
| "review PR #X" / "look at this PR" / PR URL to review | crew-pr-review | skill |
| "handle PR comments" / "what's still open on PR #X" | crew-pr-resolver | subagent |
| "reviewer says X" / "apply this suggestion" / "Copilot says..." | crew-pr-comments-eval | skill |
| "journal" / "log this" / "end of session" | crew-journal | skill |
| @crew-learn / "explain X" / "what is X" / "help me understand" | crew-learn rule → @crew-learn or @crew-creative | rule + subagents |

### Overlapping crew — when to use which

**Three PR crew members — different directions of review**:
- **crew-pr-review**: you review *someone else's* PR. Deep analysis: reads full files, traces impact, verifies tests, produces a structured review with findings by severity.
- **crew-pr-resolver**: someone reviewed *your* PR. Fetches all unresolved threads and processes them in batch — applying, adapting, rejecting, or deferring each one.
- **crew-pr-comments-eval**: the evaluation framework crew-pr-resolver uses per-comment. Also used standalone when the user pastes a single inline suggestion ("Copilot says...", "reviewer says...").

**crew-journal vs crew-creative**: crew-journal *records* an engineering session (what you delegated, what broke, CLAUDE.md candidates). crew-creative *generates ideas* from learning content and writes a learning entry. Both append to JOURNAL.md but with different schemas: crew-journal writes `Type: engineering`, crew-creative writes `Type: learning`. Use crew-journal to log work. Use crew-creative after crew-learn to ideate.

**crew-learn rule vs crew-learn agent**: The `crew-learn.mdc` rule is a lightweight router that decides whether to invoke @crew-learn or @crew-creative based on user intent. The `crew-learn.md` agent does the actual content fetching and teaching. The rule exists because Cursor needs a rule to trigger conditional routing — the agent can't route to itself.

## Add-ons

Add-ons are skills or subagents that live directly in `~/.cursor/agents/` or `~/.cursor/skills/` without being part of el-capitan. They are work-specific, internal, or experimental.

To discover available add-ons, list files in `~/.cursor/agents/` and `~/.cursor/skills/` that are NOT symlinks (real files = add-ons, symlinks = el-capitan core):

```bash
find ~/.cursor/agents ~/.cursor/skills -maxdepth 2 -type f -name '*.md' ! -type l
```

Route to add-ons the same way as core crew — match the user's trigger to the add-on's description.

## Pipeline

```
crew-spec → [YOU approve] → crew-implement → crew-diff-check → crew-commit → crew-pr-open → [review cycle] → [YOU merge]
```

The review cycle is async: after crew-pr-open, reviewers comment (minutes to days later), you run crew-pr-resolver, more comments arrive, you run crew-pr-resolver again, etc. It repeats until the PR is ready to merge.

You appear at two gates: spec approval and merge decision.

### When a gate fails

- **Spec rejected**: revise the SPEC.md based on feedback and re-present for approval. Don't start implementing.
- **Diff check finds issues**: fix the flagged issues, then re-run crew-diff-check. Don't proceed to crew-commit until clean.
- **PR comments need user input**: surface the threads that need a decision, wait for the user, then resume processing.

## Task State

Task files live at `~/.agent/tasks/<repo>/<branch>/`. Resolve automatically:

```bash
REPO=$(basename $(git rev-parse --show-toplevel))
BRANCH=$(git branch --show-current)
TASK_DIR=~/.agent/tasks/$REPO/$BRANCH
mkdir -p $TASK_DIR
```

### Before any task
1. Read `$TASK_DIR/SPEC.md` if it exists
2. Read `$TASK_DIR/PROGRESS.md` if resuming
3. If no SPEC.md exists and the task is non-trivial, draft one using `~/.agent/_SPEC_TEMPLATE.md`

### PROGRESS.md protocol

Statuses: `DRAFTING` | `APPROVED` | `IMPLEMENTING` | `DIFF_CHECK` | `COMMITTING` | `PR_OPEN` | `PR_RESOLVE` | `DONE`

`PR_RESOLVE` can repeat — after resolving a round of comments, status returns to `PR_OPEN` until the next round arrives or the PR is merged.

Update after every meaningful step:

```markdown
## Status: IMPLEMENTING
## Phase: spec → crew-implement → diff-check → commit → pr-open → [review cycle] → done
## Current: implement
## Next: diff-check

## Done
- [x] completed item

## In Progress
- [ ] current item

## Blockers
- (none)

## Next Step
What to do next in one sentence.
```

## Persistent State

| File | Purpose | Written by |
|------|---------|------------|
| `~/.agent/_SPEC_TEMPLATE.md` | Reusable spec starting point | you (manual) |
| `~/.agent/JOURNAL.md` | Append-only session log (engineering + learning) | crew-journal, @crew-creative |
| `~/.agent/tasks/<repo>/<branch>/SPEC.md` | Task specification | crew-spec |
| `~/.agent/tasks/<repo>/<branch>/PROGRESS.md` | Task progress tracker | any agent during implementation |

## Invariants

- Never start implementation without a SPEC.md
- Always update PROGRESS.md as work proceeds
- Done = acceptance criteria pass, not "looks right"
- Quality gates come from the repo's AGENTS.md, scoped to the affected package
- Never modify JOURNAL.md without being asked
